Where I work is related to the HER process of environmental stress. I actually prefer to work in my dorm room because I am unable to control the noise in the lounge. Environmental stress means there are too many things to deal with and you don’t have the ability to respond to all them. Living in the modern city, there is too much stimulation and we experience information overload. We develop strategies to lower stress, but it has costs for coping. Like less time for social inputs and redefine the boundary of social interaction.
The picture shows that there are no ticket sellers for the subway anymore, instead replaced by scanning automatic gate and ticket vendors.
#envpsy, #envpsyw1

#envpsy #envpsyw1 This relates to the HER process of environmental stress. Normally, many people would maybe not think twice about having over 4 people in this elevator. However, in having that there should only be 4 people in this elevator, may cause people to be stressed if they want to use it and there’s already 4 people. The stress may come from things like feeling that they are not able to use it and having to wait or perhaps use the stairs.

A sink filled with dirty dishes exemplifies environmental stress because it can be hard to keep up with cleaning them and it’s difficult to maintain control over the environment when there are too many dishes to clean.  #envpsy #envpsyw1

#envpsy #envpsyw1 This is an example of an environmental stress. The ongoing construction is inescapable noise leading to highest stress level in residents around the area.

The picture above is a view from my window. My house is located right next to a car wash and a train track. Because of these two places being so close, peaceful silence is rare to come by. The loud train sounds and constant noise from the car wash are examples of the HER process of environmental stress. The noise causes stress in that it makes it difficult to take long exams, and makes it difficult to concentrate on projects and homework. In class, it was discussed that students in noisier environments were more likely to fail at completing a puzzle than students in quieter environments, and that is one of the big costs of environmental stress. Even though I have lived here my whole life, the stress of covid and the college workload has increased this stress overload. #envpsyw1

After we learned about the HER process of environmental stress, especially the components of control and costs of adaptation, I began to realize the prevalence of the process in my life. The most notable example at the moment is the stress of noise in my dormitory environment. The walls of my dorm room are thin, so I can often hear noise from other people’s living spaces. however, I feel a sense of control over the noise because I can play music that I enjoy through my headphones. This also shows adaptation because I began this coping mechanism once I started living in a noisy dorm environment this semester. #envpsy #envpsyw1

This post is an example of environmental stress and the costs of coping with it. The HER process environmental stress outlines how our evolutionary mechanisms of dealing with stress are not always ideal when dealing with stresses of modern life. In fact there can be costs of the ways in which we cope with stress.

One cost that was mentioned in class, is that when students attended school near an airport (a noisy environment) they were more likely than student in a less noisy environment to fail on completing a puzzle by giving up, or having feelings of helplessness.

My bedroom in college town has very thin walls and has windows facing the street. Unfortunately, this means that the gatherings neighbors throw across the way, often sound as if they are in my own house. 

The gatherings happen often and there have been many times where I have been trying to sleep or do work. I have noticed in this situation, I will give up on doing a long reading much faster than I would if it were quiet. This action could be seen as a cost of coping with the stress overload of a noisy environment. #envpsy #envpsyw1

Here is another image of a work of art. A friend and I observed this beautiful piece in a coffee shop over the weekend. Although this does not relate directly to cities (the unit we are going over in the course), it does relate to environmental perception. Both my friend and I have different ways we evaluate and see the environment, as well as how we store information and memories. Our eyes don’t ever really see the same thing the way a camera does. This is because our eyes are subjective. The same goes for the rest of our senses. Because of this, as well as changes in mental processing, we will never experience anything exactly the way someone else has. I really enjoyed learning this!! #envpsy #envpsyw1

#envpsy #envpsyw1 An example of Environmental Stress. Leading up to our midterm project, my classmate portrayed symptoms of learned helplessness. His body is not equipped for the stresses of everyday life (ie. multiple all-nighters)

#envpsy #envpsyw1 This post relates to the paradox of human adaptivity under the HER process of environmental stress. Tonight, the sky is covered with clouds/mist so I cannot see the stars, which are apparent almost every night in Ithaca and fills the entire night sky. However, from where I grew up (Taipei, Taiwan), when I look up, I either see the view within the photo or a number of stars that I can count on one hand. This is due to light pollution as well as carbon emission that creates smog. I am lucky that I and aware of this just because I've been exposed to less  polluted areas like ithaca. However, I think children raised in cities view this as a normal and do not know what the night sky is supposed to look like without all the pollution. This also means that these people will view air pollution as less of a problem are less able recognize the presence of air pollution.

#envpsy #envpsyw1

The paradox of adaptability. This is the skyline of the  region where I live in New Delhi, India, which has an air quality index of 393 (above 100 is considered 'poor' and above 300 is 'severe'). However, most people have adapted to such air quality, and can't see or even feel the air pollution here anymore. I had also adjusted to this standard by living here for 18 years before coming to Ithaca, and the first time I returned home, it took me two weeks to re-adapt and breathe easily.

New Yorkers have become so accustomed to dealing with pollution (i.e., the pile of trash on the sidewalk) that they seem to ignore it as a whole. The capability of humans to adapt to awful environment conditions (such as this) destroys the values most important to human life and can cause health problems.

This is a picture of my mom leaving a mall this weekend I think it relates to environmental stress, specifically the cost of coping with urban life. My mom was actually urging me to move along and don’t stop all of a sudden to just take a picture of the surrounding because people might get annoyed at me... #envpsy #envpsyw1

One way I cope with this noise and stress is through the use of ear plugs. We learned in class that one coping mechanism for environmental stress is control. This photo relates to the HER process Environmental Stress. As they study, the students are experiencing environmental stress of the COVID-19 safety measures such as wearing face masks, maintaining physical distance, and keeping group size small. Change in routine for college students has a psychological and social cost that creates stress. #envpsy #envpsyw1

My current backyard relates to the HER process of environmental stress in the form of noise. Water carries noise very effectively. Since the Ogunquit river is so close to my backyard, I often hear sirens and delivery trucks as the water carries these sounds from downtown. Additionally, the woodlands are full of noises from birds and wildlife. I haven’t adapted well to the artificial sounds of sirens and trucks. However, I find myself better at identifying bird species because I’m exposed to many varieties of birds.
#envpsy #envpsy1 #envpsyw1
This is an example of Defensible space. The room is only assessable to students and provides a safe work environment

This is the group lounge at my dormitory and it relates to the HER Process Environmental Stress because when trying to work in group lounges, there tends to be a lot of noise or people which can’t be controlled so it leads to more stress. Because of the lack of control of sound and the amount of people occupying the space, I tend to work in my actual dorm room. If we had more control over noise levels, we would able to persist and continue to work in this type of environment. 
#envpsy #envpsyw1

This is the construction site on north campus right behind my house. It relates to environmental stress because there is little control for the residents over the construction schedule and the noise it makes, possibly leading to coping with overload.
#envpsy #envpsyw1

Environmental stress means there are too many things to deal with and you don’t have the ability to respond to all them. Living in the modern city, there is too much stimulation and we experience information overload. We develop strategies to lower stress, but it has costs for coping. Like less time for social inputs and redefine the boundary of social interaction.
The picture shows that there are no ticket sellers for the subway anymore, instead replaced by scanning automatic gate and ticket vendors.
#envpsy, #envpsyw1

This is my dorm room desk, the place where I check my (long) to-do list and oftentimes become stressed because of the demands of schoolwork and extracurricular responsibilities. In DEA, we discussed how stressors can be long term in modern times, often making us more prone to sickness and sedentary coping strategies. Because time and class assignments are pretty much out of my control, it can be difficult to manage this kind of stress without feeling the need to cope. 
#envpsy #envpsyw1

HER Process: Environmental Stress. This is a picture of the smoke detector in the house I rent—unfortunately it’s placed near the kitchen. The kitchen fan over the stove is broken, so anytime anyone cooks this is bound to go off. By now, we’re almost used to it. Sometimes when we cook we have the forethought to unscrew this and put it outside; usually we don’t though. Now that we’re kinda used to it, when it goes off instead of running down to see what the commotion is we just wait it out until someone takes it outside.

#envpsy #envpsyw1

Where I work is related to the HER process of environmental stress. I actually prefer to work in my dorm room because I am unable to control the noise in the lounge. Often times, small groups of students will be talking loudly and I get distracted. Other times someone plays a piano. I’m unable to focus on my work due to lack of control over the noise, get frustrated and have move back to my room where I can control the noise levels.
#envpsy #envpsyw1
